# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wilderness
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:wilderness/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:wilderness/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The generic name *Adansonia* honours Michel Adanson, the French naturalist and explorer who provided the first detailed botanical description and illustrations of *Adansonia digitata*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The baobab, however, is also known as the "upside down tree," a name attributable to the trees' overall appearance and historical myths.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobabs are among the longest-lived of vascular plants and have large flowers that are reproductive for a maximum of 15 hours.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The flowers open around dusk with sufficiently rapid movement that is detectable by the naked eye.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The fruits are large, oval to round and berry-like, and hold kidney-shaped seeds in a dry, pulpy matrix.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In the early 21st century, baobabs in southern Africa began to die off rapidly and mysteriously—the cause is yet to be determined.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Blight or pests are unlikely to have caused such rapid death, so some have speculated that the cause may have been mass dehydration.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobabs are long-lived deciduous, small to large trees from 5 to 30 m (20 to 100 ft) tall with broad trunks and compact crowns.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Young trees usually have slender, tapering trunks, often with a swollen base.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Mature trees have massive trunks that are bottle-shaped or cylindrical and tapered from bottom to top.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The trunk is made of fibrous wood arranged in concentric rings, although rings are not always formed annually and so cannot be used to determine the age of individual trees.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Tree diameter fluctuates with rainfall so it is thought that water may be stored in the trunk.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobab trees have two types of shoots—long, green vegetative ones, and stout, woody reproductive ones.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Branches can be massive and spread out horizontally from the trunk or are ascending.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Leaves are palmately compound in mature trees, but seedlings and regenerating shoots may have simple leaves.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The transition to compound leaves comes with age and may be gradual.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Leaves have 5–11 leaflets, with the largest ones in the middle and may be stalkless or with short petioles.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Leaflets may have toothed or smooth edges, and may be hairless or have simple-to-clumped hairs.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobabs have stipules at the base of the leaves, but the stipules are soon shed in most species.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobabs are deciduous, shedding leaves during the dry season.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In most *Adansonia* species, the flowers are borne on short erect or spreading stalks in the axils of the leaves near the tips of reproductive shoots.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Only *A. digitata* has flowers and fruits set on long, hanging stalks.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] There is usually only a single flower in an axil, but sometimes flowers occur in pairs.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] They are large, showy and strongly scented.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Opening is rapid and movement of the flower parts is fast enough to be visible.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Most *Adansonia* species are pollinated by bats.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Flowers may remain attached to the trees for several days, but the reproductive phase is very short, with pollen shed during the first night and stigmas shriveled by the morning.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The flower is made up of an outer 5-lobed calyx, and an inner ring of petals set around a fused tube of stamens.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The outer lobes of the calyx are usually green (brown in *A. grandidieri*) and in bud are joined almost to the tip.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] As the flower opens, the calyx lobes split apart and become coiled or bent back (reflexed) at the base of the flower.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The inner surface of the lobes are silky-hairy and cream, pink, or red.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Sometimes the lobes do not separate cleanly, distorting the shape of the flower as they bend back.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The calyx lobes remain fused at the base, leaving a feature (calyx tube) that has nectar-producing tissue and that is cup-shaped, flat or tubular; the form of the calyx tube varies with species.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The flowers have a central tube (staminal tube) made up of fused stalks of stamens (filaments), with unfused filaments above.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] A densely hairy ovary is enclosed in the staminal tube, and a long style tipped with a stigma emerges from the filaments.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Petals are set near the base of the staminal tube and are variable in shape and colour.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The flowers, when fresh, may be white, cream, bright yellow or dark red, but fade quickly, often turning reddish when dried.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The fruit of the baobabs is one of their distinguishing features.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] It is large, oval-to-round, and berry-like in most species (usually less than 10 centimetres (3.9 in) long in *A. madagascariensis*.).
[src:wilderness/adansonia] It has a dry, hard outer shell of variable thickness.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In most species, the shell is indehiscent (does not break open easily).
[src:wilderness/adansonia] *A. gibbosa* is the only species with fruits that crack while still on the tree, which then tend to break open upon landing on the ground.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Inside the outer shell, kidney-shaped seeds 10–15(−20) mm long are set in a dry pulp.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The earliest written reports of baobab are from a 14th-century travelogue by the Arab traveler Ibn Battuta.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The first botanical description was in the *De medicina Aegyptiorum* by Prospero Alpini (1592), looking at fruits that he observed in Egypt from an unknown source.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] They were called *Bahobab*, possibly from the Arabic أَبُو حِبَاب *abū ḥibāb* meaning "many-seeded fruit".
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The French explorer and botanist Michel Adanson (1727–1806) observed a baobab tree in 1749 on the island of Sor in Senegal, and wrote the first detailed botanical description of the full tree, accompanied with illustrations.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Recognizing the connection to the fruit described by Alpini he called the genus Baobab.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Linnaeus later renamed the genus *Adansonia*, to honour Adanson, but use of baobab as one of the common names has persisted.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The genus *Adansonia* is in the subfamily Bombacoideae, within the family Malvaceae in the order Malvales.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The subfamily Bombacoideae was previously treated as the Bombacaceae family but it is no longer recognized at the rank of family by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group I 1998, II 2003 or the Kubitzki system 2003.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The closest living relatives of *Adansonia* within Bombacoideae are the South American genera: *Cavanillesia*, *Scleronema*, *Catostemma*, and *Aguiaria.* There are eight accepted species of *Adansonia*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] A new species (*Adansonia kilima* Pettigrew, et al.), was described in 2012, found in high-elevation sites in eastern and southern Africa.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] This, however, is no longer recognized as a distinct species but considered a synonym of *A. digitata*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Some high-elevation trees in Tanzania show different genetics and morphology, but further study is needed to determine if recognition of them as a separate species is warranted.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The genus *Adansonia* is further divided into three sections.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Section Adansonia includes only *A. digitata*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] This species has hanging flowers and fruit, set on long flowering stalks.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] This is the type species for the genus *Adansonia*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] All species of *Adansonia* except *A. digitata* are diploid; *A. digitata* is tetraploid.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Section Brevitubae includes *A. grandidieri* and *A. suarexensis*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] These are species with flower buds that set on short pedicles and that are approximately twice as long as wide.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The other species are all classified within the section Longitubae.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] They also have flowers/fruits set on short pedicels, but the flower buds are five or more times as long as wide.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] As of July 2020, eight species of *Adansonia* have been recognized, with six endemic to Madagascar, one native to mainland Africa and the Arabian Peninsula, and one native to Australia.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The mainland African species (*Adansonia digitata*) also occurs on Madagascar, but it is not a native of that island.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] African Baobabs were introduced in ancient times to south Asia and possibly Australia (if it is ancestral to the Australian baobab), and during the colonial era to the Caribbean.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] They are also established in the island nation of Cape Verde.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] A ninth species was described in 2012 (*Adansonia kilima* Pettigrew, et al.), but is no longer recognized as a distinct species.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The oldest splits within *Adansonia* are likely no older than 15 million years.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The African and Australian baobabs are closely related, and thus the Australian species represents dispersal from Africa, though there is some dispute as to whether the dispersal was human-vectored.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The Malagasy species are important components of the Madagascar dry deciduous forests.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Within that biome, *Adansonia madagascariensis* and *A. rubrostipa* occur specifically in the Anjajavy Forest, sometimes growing out of the tsingy limestone itself.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] *A. digitata* has been called "a defining icon of African bushland".
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The tree also grows wild in Sudan in the regions of Darfur and the state of Kordofan.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The locals call it *gongolaze* and use its fruits as food and medicine and use the tree trunks as reservoirs to save water.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobabs store water in the trunk (up to 120,000 litres or 32,000 US gallons) to endure harsh drought conditions.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] All occur in seasonally arid areas, and are deciduous, shedding their leaves during the dry season.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Across Africa, the oldest and largest baobabs began to die in the early 21st century, likely from a combination of drought and rising temperatures.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The trees appear to become parched, then become dehydrated and unable to support their massive trunks.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobabs are important as nest sites for birds, in particular the mottled spinetail and four species of weaver.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Radiocarbon dating has provided data on a few individuals of *A. digitata*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The Panke baobab in Zimbabwe was some 2,450 years old when it died in 2011, making it the oldest angiosperm ever documented, and two other trees—*Dorslandboom* in Namibia and *Glencoe* in South Africa—were estimated to be approximately 2,000 years old.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Another specimen known as *Grootboom* was dated and found to be at least 1,275 years old.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The Glencoe Baobab, a specimen of *A. digitata* in Limpopo Province, South Africa, was considered to be the largest living individual, with a maximum circumference of 47 m (154 ft) and a diameter of about 15.9 m (52 ft).
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The tree has since split into two parts, so the widest individual trunk may now be that of the Sunland Baobab, or Platland tree, also in South Africa.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The diameter of this tree at ground level is 9.3 m (31 ft) and its circumference at breast height is 34 m (112 ft).
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Two large baobabs growing in Tsimanampetsotse National Park were also studied using radiocarbon dating.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] One called *Grandmother* is made up of three fused trunks of different ages, with the oldest part of the tree an estimated 1,600 years old.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The second, "polygamous baobab", has six fused stems, and is an estimated 1,000 years old.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The tree's leaves may be eaten as a leaf vegetable.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The white pith in the fruit of the Australian baobab (*A. gregorii*) tastes like sherbet.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] It is a good source of vitamin C, potassium, carbohydrates, and phosphorus.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The dried fruit powder of *A. digitata*, baobab powder, contains about 11% water, 80% carbohydrates (50% fiber), and modest levels of various nutrients, including riboflavin, calcium, magnesium, potassium, iron, and phytosterols, with low levels of protein and fats.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Vitamin C content, described as variable in different samples, was in a range of 74 to 163 milligrams (1.14 to 2.52 gr) per 100 grams (3.5 oz) of dried powder.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In 2008, baobab dried fruit pulp was authorized in the EU as a *safe food ingredient*, and later in the year was granted GRAS (*generally recognized as safe*) status in the United States.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In Angola, the dry fruit of *A. digitata* is usually boiled, and the broth is used for juices or as the base for a type of ice cream known as *gelado de múcua*.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In Zimbabwe, the fruit of *A. digitata* is eaten fresh or the crushed crumbly pulp is stirred into porridge and drinks.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In Tanzania, the dry pulp of *A. digitata* is added to sugarcane to aid fermentation in brewing (beermaking).
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The seeds of some species are a source of vegetable oil.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The fruit pulp and seeds of *A. grandidieri* and *A. za* are eaten fresh.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Some baobab species are sources of fiber, dye, and fuel.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Indigenous Australians used the native species *A. gregorii* for several products, making string from the root fibers and decorative crafts from the fruits.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobab oil from the seed is also used in cosmetics, particularly in moisturizers.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] Baobab trees hold cultural and spiritual significance in many African societies.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] They are often the sites of communal gatherings, storytelling, and rituals.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] An unusual baobab was the namesake of Kukawa, formerly the capital of the Bornu Empire southwest of Lake Chad in Central Africa.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] In the novel *The Little Prince*, the titular character takes care to root out baobabs that try to grow on his tiny planet home.
[src:wilderness/adansonia] The fearsome, grasping baobab trees, researchers have contended, were meant to represent Nazism attempting to destroy the planet.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The achievement of these objectives requires an open management process which seeks to include past, present and future stakeholders.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management needs to at least maintain political openness, but usually aims to create it.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management must therefore be a scientific and social process.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] It must focus on the development of new institutions and institutional strategies in balance with scientific hypothesis and experimental frameworks (resilience.org).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management can proceed as either passive or active adaptive management, depending on how learning takes place.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Passive adaptive management values learning only insofar as it improves decision outcomes (i.e. passively), as measured by the specified utility function.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In contrast, active adaptive management explicitly incorporates learning as part of the objective function, and hence, decisions which improve learning are valued over those which do not.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In both cases, as new knowledge is gained, the models are updated and optimal management strategies are derived accordingly.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Thus, while learning occurs in both cases, it is treated differently.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Often, deriving actively adaptive policies is technically very difficult, which prevents it being more commonly applied.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The use of adaptive management techniques can be traced back to peoples from ancient civilisations.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] For example, the Yap people of Micronesia have been using adaptive management techniques to sustain high population densities in the face of resource scarcity for thousands of years (Falanruw 1984).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In using these techniques, the Yap people have altered their environment creating, for example, coastal mangrove depressions and seagrass meadows to support fishing and termite resistant wood (Stankey and Shinder 1997).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The origin of the adaptive management concept can be traced back to ideas of scientific management pioneered by Frederick Taylor in the early 1900s (Haber 1964).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] While the term "adaptive management" evolved in natural resource management workshops through decision makers, managers and scientists focussing on building simulation models to uncover key assumptions and uncertainties.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Two ecologists at The University of British Columbia, C.S.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Holling and C.J Walters further developed the adaptive management approach as they distinguished between passive and active adaptive management practice.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Kai Lee, notable Princeton physicist, expanded upon the approach in the late 1970s and early 1980s while pursuing a post-doctorate degree at UC Berkeley.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The approach was further developed at the International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA) in Vienna, Austria, while C.S.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In 1992, Hilbourne described three learning models for federal land managers, around which adaptive management approaches could be developed, these are reactive, passive and active.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management has probably been most frequently applied in Yap, Australia and North America, initially applied in fishery management, but received more broad application in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] One of the most successful applications of adaptive management has been in the area of waterfowl harvest management in North America, most notably for the mallard.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management in a conservation project and program context can trace its roots back to at least the early 1990s, with the establishment of the Biodiversity Support Program (BSP) in 1989.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] BSP was a USAID-funded consortium of WWF, The Nature Conservancy (TNC), and World Resources Institute (WRI).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Its Analysis and Adaptive Management Program sought to understand the conditions under which certain conservation strategies were most effective and to identify lessons learned across conservation projects.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] When BSP ended in 2001, TNC and Foundations of Success (FOS, a non-profit which grew out of BSP) continued to actively work in promoting adaptive management for conservation projects and programs.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The approaches used included Conservation by Design (TNC) and Measures of Success (FOS).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In 2004, the Conservation Measures Partnership (CMP) – which includes several former BSP members – developed a common set of standards and guidelines for applying adaptive management to conservation projects and programs.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Applying adaptive management in a conservation or ecosystem management project involves the integration of project/program design, management, and monitoring to systematically test assumptions in order to adapt and learn.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The concept of adaptive management is not restricted to natural resources or ecosystem management, as similar concepts have been applied to international development programming.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This has often been a recognition to the "wicked" nature of many development challenges and the limits of traditional planning processes.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] One of the principal changes facing international development organizations is the need to be more flexible, adaptable and focused on learning.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This is reflected in international development approaches such as Doing Development Differently, Politically Informed Programming and Problem Driven Iterative Adaptation.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] One recent example of the use of adaptive management by international development donors is the planned Global Learning for Adaptive Management (GLAM) programme to support adaptive management in Department for International Development and USAID.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The program is establishing a centre for learning about adaptive management to support the utilization and accessibility of adaptive management.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In addition, donors have been focused on amending their own programmatic guidance to reflect the importance of learning within programs: for instance, USAID's recent focus in their ADS guidance on the importance of collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This is also reflected in Department for International Development's Smart Rules that provide the operating framework for their programs including the use of evidence to inform their decisions.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] There are a variety of tools used to operationalize adaptive management in programs, such as learning agendas and decision cycles.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Collaborating, learning and adapting (CLA) is a concept related to the operationalizing of adaptive management in international development that describes a specific way of designing, implementing, adapting and evaluating programs.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] 3. adapting strategically based on applied learning.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] CLA practices have tangible benefits; for instance, a recent study recently found that companies "which apply more data-driven and adaptive leadership practices perform better" when examined against those which focus less on those practices.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] CLA integrates three closely connected concepts within the organizational theory literature: namely collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] There is evidence of the benefits of collaborating internally within an organization and externally with organizations.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Much of the production and transmission of knowledge—both explicit knowledge and tacit knowledge—occurs through collaboration.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] There is evidence for the importance of collaboration among individuals and groups for innovation, knowledge production, and diffusion—for example, the benefits of staff interacting with one another and transmitting knowledge.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The importance of collaboration is closely linked to the ability of organizations to collectively learn from each other, a concept noted in the literature on learning organizations.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] CLA has been linked to a part of USAID's commitment to becoming a learning organization.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] CLA represents an approach to combine strategic collaboration, continuous learning, and adaptive management.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] A part of integrating the CLA approach is providing tools and resources, such as the Learning Lab, to staff and partner organizations.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The CLA approach is detailed for USAID staff in the recently revised program policy guidance.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a systematic process for improving environmental management policies and practices is the traditional application however, the adaptive management framework can also be applied to other sectors seeking sustainability solutions such as business and community development.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a strategy emphasizes the need to change with the environment and to learn from doing.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Adaptive management applied to ecosystems makes overt sense when considering ever changing environmental conditions.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The flexibility and constant learning of an adaptive management approach is also a logical application for organizations seeking sustainability methodologies.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Businesses pursuing sustainability strategies would employ an adaptive management framework to ensure that the organization is prepared for the unexpected and geared for change.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] By applying an adaptive management approach the business begins to function as an integrated system adjusting and learning from a multi-faceted network of influences not just environmental but also, economic and social (Dunphy, Griffths, & Benn, 2007).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The goal of any sustainable organization guided by adaptive management principals must be to engage in active learning to direct change towards sustainability (Verine, 2008).
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This "learning to manage by managing to learn" (Bormann BT, 1993) will be at the core of a sustainable business strategy.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Sustainable community development requires recognition of the relationship between environment, economics and social instruments within the community.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] An adaptive management approach to creating sustainable community policy and practice also emphasizes the connection and confluence of those elements.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] A practical example of adaptive management as a tool for sustainability was the application of a modified variation of adaptive management using artvoice, photovoice, and agent-based modeling in a participatory social framework of action.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This application was used in field research on tribal lands to first identify the environmental issue and impact of illegal trash dumping and then to discover a solution through iterative agent-based modeling using NetLogo on a theoretical "regional cooperative clean-energy economy".
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This cooperative economy incorporated a mixed application of: traditional trash recycling and a waste-to-fuels process of carbon recycling of non-recyclable trash into ethanol fuel.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This industrial waste-to-fuels application was inspired by pioneering work of the Canadian-based company, Enerkem.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] See Bruss, 2012 - PhD dissertation: Human Environment Interactions and Collaborative Adaptive Capacity Building in a Resilience Framework, GDPE Colorado State University.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] It is difficult to test the effectiveness of adaptive management in comparison to other management approaches.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] One challenge is that once a system is managed using one approach it is difficult to determine how another approach would have performed in exactly the same situation.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] One study tested the effectiveness of formal passive adaptive management in comparison to human intuition by having natural resource management students make decisions about how to harvest a hypothetical fish population in an online computer game.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The students on average performed poorly in comparison to the computer programs implementing passive adaptive management.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Collaborative adaptive management is often celebrated as an effective way to deal with natural resource management under high levels of conflict, uncertainty and complexity.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The effectiveness of these efforts can be constrained by both social and technical barriers.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] In Colorado, USA, a ten-year, ranch-scale (2590 ha) experiment began in 2012 at the Agricultural Research Service (ARS) Central Plains Experimental range to evaluate the effectiveness and process of collaborative adaptive management on rangelands.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] The Collaborative Adaptive Rangeland Management or “CARM” project monitors outcomes from yearling steer grazing management on 10, 130 ha pastures conducted by a group of conservationists, ranchers, and public employees, and researchers.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] This team compares ecological monitoring data tracking profitability and conservation outcomes with outcomes from a “traditional” management treatment: a second set of ten pastures managed without adaptive decision making but with the same stocking rate.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Early evaluations of the project by social scientists offer insights for more effective adaptive management.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] First, trust is primary and essential to learning in adaptive management, not a side benefit.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Second, practitioners cannot assume that extensive monitoring data or large-scale efforts will automatically facilitate successful collaborative adaptive management.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Active, long-term efforts to build trust among scientists and stakeholders are also important.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Finally, explicit efforts to understand, share and respect multiple types of manager knowledge, including place-based ecological knowledge practiced by local managers, is necessary to manage adaptively for multiple conservation and livelihood goals on rangelands.
[src:wilderness/adaptive-management] Practitioners can expect adaptive management to be a complex, non-linear process shaped by social, political and ecological processes, as well as by data collection and interpretation.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The **Adirondack Park** is the designation for a large area of northeastern New York centered on the Adirondack Mountains.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Like Catskill Park to the south, the area is unusual in the United States because, while the entire area is considered "parkland", about 52 percent of the land within the boundary consists of privately owned inholdings.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The remaining 48 percent is publicly owned by the state as part of the Forest Preserve.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Use of public and private lands in the park is regulated by the Adirondack Park Agency.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The park was established in 1892 for "the free use of all the people for their health and pleasure", and for watershed protection.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] At 6.1 million acres (25,000 km2), it is the largest park in the contiguous United States.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park contains the 46 High Peaks, 2,800 lakes and ponds, 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of rivers and streams, and an estimated 200,000 acres (81,000 ha) of old-growth forests.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It is home to 105 towns and villages, as well as numerous farms, businesses, and a timber-harvesting industry.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The park has a population of 130,000 permanent and 200,000 seasonal residents, and sees over 12.4 million annual visitors.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The inclusion of human communities has been described as one of the most successful experiments in conserving previously developed lands in the industrialized world.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Forest Preserve was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1963.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Before the 19th century, the wilderness was viewed as desolate and forbidding.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] As Romanticism developed in the United States, the view of wilderness became more positive, as seen in the writings of James Fenimore Cooper, Ralph Waldo Emerson, John Muir, and Henry David Thoreau.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The 1849 publication of Joel Tyler Headley's *Adirondack; or, Life in the Woods* triggered the development of hotels and stage coach lines.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] William Henry Harrison Murray's 1869 wilderness guidebook depicted the area as a place of relaxation and pleasure rather than a natural obstacle.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Financier and railroad promoter Thomas Clark Durant acquired a large tract of central Adirondack land and built a railroad from Saratoga Springs to North Creek.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] By 1875, there were more than two hundred hotels in the Adirondacks including Paul Smith's Hotel.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] About this time, the Great Camps were developed.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Following the Civil War, Reconstruction Era economic expansion led to an increase in logging and deforestation, especially in the southern Adirondacks.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1870 Verplanck Colvin made the first recorded ascent of Seward Mountain during which he saw the extensive damage done by lumbermen.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] He wrote a report which was read at the Albany Institute and printed by the New York State Museum of Natural History.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1872 he was named to the newly created post of Superintendent of the Adirondack Survey and given a $1000 budget by the state legislature to institute a survey of the Adirondacks.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1873 he wrote a report arguing that if the Adirondack watershed was allowed to deteriorate, it would threaten the viability of the Erie Canal, which was then vital to New York's economy.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] He was subsequently appointed superintendent of the New York state land survey.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1873, he recommended the creation of a state forest preserve covering the entire Adirondack region.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This forestry law also established a Forest Commission which was charged with care, custody, control and superintendence of the Forest Preserve.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1902, the legislature passed a bill defining the Adirondack Park for the first time in terms of the counties and towns within it.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1912 the legislature further clarified that the park included the privately owned lands within it as well as the public holdings.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The restrictions on development and lumbering embodied in Article XIV have withstood many challenges from timber interests, hydropower projects and large-scale tourism development interests.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Further, the language of the article, and decades of legal experience in its defense, are widely recognized as having laid the foundation for the U.S.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] As a result of the legal protections, many pieces of the original forest of the Adirondacks have never been logged and are old-growth forest.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Early in the 1900s, recreational use increased dramatically.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The State Conservation Department (now the Department of Environmental Conservation) responded by building more facilities: boat docks, tent platforms, lean-tos, and telephone and electrical lines.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] With the building of Interstate 87 in the 1960s, private lands came under great pressure for development.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This growing crisis led to the 1971 creation of the Adirondack Park Agency (APA) to develop long-range land-use plans for both the public and private lands within the Blue Line.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In consultation with the DEC, the APA formulated the State Land Master Plan which was adopted into law in 1973.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The plan is designed to channel much of the future growth in the Park around existing communities, where roads, utilities, services, and supplies already exist.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 2008 The Nature Conservancy purchased Follensby Pond – about 14,600 acres (5,900 ha) of private land inside the park boundary – for $16 million.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The group plans to sell the land to the state, which will add it to the forest preserve once the remaining leases for recreational hunting and fishing on the property expire.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The park is managed by two state agencies: the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, created in 1970 and headquartered in Albany; and the Adirondack Park Agency, created in 1971 and headquartered in Ray Brook.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Noted forest ranger Clarence Petty sat on the commission that recommend the creation of the APA.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This system of management is distinctly different from New York's state park system, which is managed by the Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] According to the State Land Master Plan, state lands are classified.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park Land Use and Development Plan (APLUDP) applies to private land use and development.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It defines APA jurisdiction and is designed to direct and cluster development to minimize impact.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] 49% of the park is privately owned, 45% state owned, and 6% is water.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] State wilderness areas account for 46% of the area of the park which is not private property.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] They are managed like federal wilderness areas.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] These areas are far more affected by nature than humanity, to the extent that the latter is practically unnoticeable, for example virgin forest.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] No powered vehicles are allowed in wilderness areas.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The 19,000-acre (77 km2) Saint Regis Canoe Area, presently the only Canoe Area in the park, operates under essentially the same conditions as the Wilderness Areas.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Private organizations are buying land in order to sell it back to New York State to be added to the public portion of the Park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are more than 3,000 lakes and 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of streams and rivers.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Many areas within the park are devoid of settlements and distant from usable roads.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The fur trade led to the near-extirpation of the beaver in the park by 1893.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Other species, such as the moose, elk, wolf, and cougar were hunted either for their meat, for sport, or because they were seen as a threat to livestock.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The historical presence in the area of animals such as the Canada lynx, wolverine, and caribou are unclear.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Reintroduction efforts for beaver began around 1904 by introducing the remaining beaver in the Adirondacks to imported Canadian ones, and later, from Yellowstone.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The population quickly grew to around 2000 in roughly ten years, and around 20,000 in 1921, with the addition of beavers in different areas of the park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Although the reintroduction was marked as an ecological success, the elevated beaver population was found to have negative economic impacts on waterways and timber sources.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The introduction of elk to the Adirondacks, a species that is unclear to have ever previously occupied the region, would continue after the late-19th century.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] After two previously failed attempts to introduce elk, in 1903, over 150 elk were reported by the State of New York Forest, Fish, and Game Commission to have been released and surviving in the park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The elk population increased for several years, only to decline and ultimately disappear due to poaching.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] To protect and maintain the elk population in the future, the DeBar Mountain Game Refuge was established within the Forest Preserve.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This act of preserving the species was motivated by hunting purposes rather than an ecological or natural aspect.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Game Refuge was defined by a wire fence, numerous postings, and caretakers employed by the State.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This effort to control nature was also observed in the actions of the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC), work crews who established access roads and water-supply expansion.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] A negative result of the CCC coming to the Park was their trapping and killing of "vermin", which included animals such as hawks, owls, fox, and weasels that preyed on other species sought after by hunters and fishermen.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This proved to have unanticipated ecological consequences (most notably the overpopulation of deer) which were reported by the New York State Conservation Department in 1945.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Ongoing efforts have been made to reintroduce native fauna that had been lost in the park during earlier exploitation.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are 53 known species of mammals that live in the park, including raccoons, moose, black bears, coyotes, opossums, beavers, porcupines, fishers, martens, river otters, and bobcats.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Notable birds of prey that breed in the park include the red-tailed hawk, broad-winged hawk, peregrine falcon, osprey, great horned owl, barred owl, northern saw-whet owl, and turkey vulture.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Other notable breeding birds include northern forest specialists like Canada jays, black-backed woodpeckers, boreal chickadees, spruce grouse, palm warblers, and yellow-bellied flycatchers.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The park is home to 39 species of amphibians and reptiles.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Frog species include the American bullfrog, American toad, gray treefrog, green frog (*Lithobates clamitans*), mink frog, northern leopard frog, pickerel frog, spring peeper, and wood frog.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] As of June 2025, it is not clear whether all frog populations are stable or will remain stable amid the global decline in amphibian populations.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Some species, such as the green frog, pickerel frog, spring peeper, and wood frog, are considered stable or of low conservation concern in the Adirondack area.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] However, multiple species have experienced problems with breeding cycles.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] For example, wood frogs in Adirondack Park experienced die-offs caused by ranavirus in the late 2000s, following a broader trend of disease outbreaks among amphibians in the Northeastern United States.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are 7 species of turtle: Blanding's turtle, the eastern musk turtle (*Sternotherus odoratus*), northern map turtle, painted turtle, common snapping turtle, spotted turtle, and wood turtle (*Glyptemys insculpta*).
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The spotted turtle and wood turtle are listed as species of special concern in the state of New York.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] An estimated 7–10 million tourists visit the park annually.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are numerous accommodations, including cabins, hunting lodges, villas and hotels, in and around Lake Placid, Lake George, Saranac Lake, Old Forge, Schroon Lake and the St.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Although the climate during the winter months can be severe, with temperatures falling below −30 °F (−34.4 °C), a number of sanatoriums were located there in the early twentieth century because of the positive effect the air had on tuberculosis patients.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Golf courses within the park border include the Ausable Club, the Lake Placid Club, and the Ticonderoga Country Club.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Many of the Adirondack Mountains, such as Whiteface Mountain (Wilmington), Mt.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Pisgah (Saranac Lake), Gore Mountain (North Creek), West Mountain (Glens Falls), Hickory (Luzerne), and Mt.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Morris (Tupper Lake) have been developed as ski areas.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Hunting and fishing are allowed in the Adirondack Park, although in many places there are strict regulations.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Because of these regulations, the large tourist population has not overfished the area, and as such, the brooks, rivers, ponds and lakes are home to large trout and black bass populations.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Although restricted from much of the park, snowmobile enthusiasts can ride on a large network of trails.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park Agency visitor interpretive centers are designed to help orient visitors to the park via educational programs, exhibits, and interpretive trails.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Educational programs are available for school groups as well as the general public.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Wild Center in Tupper Lake offers extensive exhibits about the natural history of the region, including a 1,000-foot-long series of elevated bridges that rise up over the forest on the center's campus.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Many of the exhibits are live and include native turtles, otter, birds, fish and porcupines.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The center, which is open year-round, has trails to a river and pond on its campus.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Experience in Blue Mountain Lake contains an extensive collection about the human settlement of the Park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Six Nation Indian Museum in Franklin has as a mission to provide education about Iroquois (also known as Haudenosaunee) culture, particularly environmental ethics, and to reinforce traditional values and philosophies.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] This is done via artifacts, presentations, and hosted visits.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The 46 highest mountains in the park, known as Adirondack High Peaks, were thought to be over 4,000 feet (1,219 m) when climbed by brothers Robert and George Marshall between 1918 and 1924.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Surveys have since shown that four of these peaks — Blake Peak, Cliff Mountain, Nye Mountain and Couchsachraga Peak — are in fact just slightly under 4,000 feet (1,219 m).
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Some hikers try to climb all of the original 46 peaks, and there is a Forty Sixers club for those who have done so.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Cliffs with rock climbing and ice climbing routes are scattered throughout the park boundaries.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The surface of many of the lakes lies at an elevation above 1,500 ft (457 m); their shores are usually rocky and irregular, and the wild scenery within their vicinity has made them very attractive to tourists.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It is the site of the Adirondack Canoe Classic.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Flatwater and whitewater canoeing and kayaking are very popular.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Hundreds of lakes, ponds, and slow-moving streams link to provide routes ranging from under one mile (1.6 km) to weeklong treks.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Whitewater kayaking and canoeing are popular on many free-flowing rivers in the Adirondacks, particularly in the spring.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Whitewater rafting trips are run in the spring on the Moose River near Old Forge.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Raft trips are possible on the Hudson River near North River from April to October, due to dam releases provided by the Town of Indian Lake.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Motorboating is formally restricted on only a few bodies of water.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park Agency visitor interpretive centers (or VICs) were established in 1989 and 1990.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The centers helped orient visitors to the park via educational programs, exhibits, and interpretive trails.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Educational programs were available for school groups as well as the general public.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Due to state fiscal and budgetary constraints, Governor David Paterson marked the VICs for closure on December 31, 2010, and in 2011, New York State sold both visitor centers to nearby colleges.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Paul Smith's VIC opened in 1989 and in 2011 became the Paul Smith's College VIC, owned and operated by Paul Smith's College.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Located on approximately 2,700 acres (11 km2) in Paul Smiths, New York, near Paul Smith's College, the Paul Smith's College Visitor Interpretive Center has approximately 25 miles of maintained trails.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Throughout the property visitors will encounter every habitat type found in the Adirondack Park except alpine.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Each spring the PSC VIC hosts the Great Adirondack Birding Festival.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Throughout the year visitors can partake of guided interpretive walks, regular outdoor activities, naturalist-led canoe paddles on Barnum Pond, and assorted workshops and programs.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In the winter the trails are open for snowshoeing and cross-country skiing.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Interpretive Center is situated on ESF's Huntington Wildlife Forest, a 15,000-acre (61 km2) biological field station the college has operated in Newcomb since 1932, and also home to the college's Adirondack Ecological Center.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Located on 236 acres (0.96 km2) at the outlet of Rich Lake, the center has approximately three and a half miles of interpretive trails.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Habitats include lakeshore, wetlands, old growth forest, and mixed northern forest.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Throughout the year staff conduct naturalist-led trail walks, guided paddles on Rich Lake, and assorted workshops and lectures.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] All trails are open in the winter for snowshoeing; cross-country skiing is permitted, and requires varying degrees of skill depending on trails and conditions.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Management and ownership of the Newcomb center was assumed by the SUNY College of Environmental Science and Forestry (SUNY-ESF) on July 1, 2010, with program responsibility beginning January 1, 2011.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] While the park does contain large areas of wilderness, some areas developed to a varying degree.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Interstate 87 or *Northway*, completed in the 1970s, runs north to south through the eastern edge of the park, connecting Montreal to Upstate New York.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The park is traversed by military training routes of the Air National Guard.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are six business parks in Essex County, of which two have certified shovel ready sites.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are many maple syrup producers, and their work is documented at the American Maple Museum at Croghan.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Educational institutions include the State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry and Paul Smith's College.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Railways were used extensively from about 1871 to the 1930s for passenger transport and freight.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Passenger transport was supplemented by stagecoaches.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The principal rail company to the major resorts was the New York Central Railroad.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Destinations within the park, served by its *Adirondack Division*, included Loon Lake, Saranac Lake, Lake Placid, Santa Clara, Tupper Lake, Thendara, Old Forge, and Lake Clear.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] On the edge of the park boundary were Brandon and St.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] North of the park were Moira and Malone.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1920 there were 10 scheduled daily passenger train stops in Big Moose.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Starting in the 1930s, people began to use automobiles rather than the train.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] However, through the 1950s and until 1961, there was a daily day train and a daily night train in each direction to Lake Placid station.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Passenger train service ended on April 24, 1965.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Freight service to and from the Adirondacks also declined after World War II.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Penn Central Transportation Company, successor to the New York Central, continued freight service between Utica and Lake Placid until it abandoned the Remsen-Lake Placid line in 1972.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There are many small airstrips and lakes for seaplanes to land but there is only one commercial airport within the park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Regional Airport sits just outside of the Village of Saranac Lake in the hamlet of Lake Clear, town of Harrietstown.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The airport's commercial airline service is funded by the government's Essential Air Service program, which provides small communities with flights to major cities that could not be supported without the help of government funding.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Plattsburgh International Airport is located 10 miles (16 km) outside the park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] There is an Adirondack architectural style that relates to the rugged style associated with the Great Camps.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The builders of these camps used native building materials and sited their buildings within an irregular wooded landscape.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] These camps for the wealthy were built to provide a primitive, rustic appearance while avoiding the problems of in-shipping materials from elsewhere.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1903 and 1908 fires consumed nearly 1 million acres (400,000 hectares) of forest.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] In 1909, the first Adirondack fire lookout tower, made of logs, was erected on Mount Morris and many others were built over the next several years.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] At one time or another, there have been fire towers at 57 locations in today's Adirondack Park.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The system worked for about 60 years, but has since been replaced by other technologies.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Today, 34 towers survive in the region and many have been restored and are accessible to the public.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Some in the Adirondack Forest Preserve have been listed on the National Register of Historic Places, including those on the following mountains: Arab, Azure, Blue, Hadley, Kane, Loon Lake, Poke-O-Moonshine, St.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] McIntyre Furnace & McNaughton Cottage: an 1853 blast furnace, the 1832 McNaughton Cottage, the remains of the Tahawus Club era buildings, and the early mining-related sites.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Regis Presbyterian church: designed by prolific Saranac Lake architect William L.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Coulter and built on land donated by Paul Smith.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Construction funds came from donations from the congregation, which was largely made up of summer residents.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It served as a church from 1899 to 2010.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Bow Bridge: The Bow Bridge in Hadley is one of only two parabolic or lenticular truss bridges in the region and one of only about 50 remaining in the country.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It was built over the Sacandaga River by the Berlin Iron Bridge Co. in 1885.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Jay Covered Bridge over the Ausable River.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The Adirondack lean-to is a three sided log shelter.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Saranac Village at Will Rogers: a Tudor Revival style retirement community, was constructed in 1930 as a tuberculosis treatment facility for vaudeville performers.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Due to the subsequent decline of vaudeville performers, and an eventual cure for tuberculosis, its doors closed in 1975.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] After sitting unused for twenty years, it was bought in 1998 by the Alpine Adirondack Association, LLC and reopened in January 2000 as a retirement community.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Camp Santanoni was once a private estate of approximately 13,000 acres (53 km2), and now is the property of the state, at Newcomb.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It was a residential complex of about 45 buildings.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Now a National Historic Landmark, this is one of the earliest examples of the Great Camps of the Adirondacks.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] At the time of completion in 1893, Camp Santanoni was regarded as the grandest of all such Adirondack camps.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Wellscroft, at Upper Jay, is a Tudor Revival–style summer estate home.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It is a long, 2+1⁄2-story, building with several projecting bays, porches, gables and dormers, a porte cochere and a service wing.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The rear facade features a large semi-circular projection.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The first-story exterior is faced in native fieldstone.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] The interior features a number of Arts and Crafts style design features.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Also on the property are a power house, fire house, gazebo, root cellar, reservoir, ruins of the caretaker's house and carriage house, and the remains of the landscaped grounds.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2004.
[src:wilderness/adirondack-park] Prospect Point Camp: a Great Camp notable for its unusual chalets inspired by European hunting lodges.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Adventure tourists may have the motivation to achieve mental states characterized as rush or flow, resulting from stepping outside their comfort zone.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] This may be from experiencing culture shock or by performing acts requiring significant effort and involve some degree of risk, real or perceived, or physical danger.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] This may include activities such as mountaineering, trekking, bungee jumping, mountain biking, cycling, canoeing, scuba diving, rafting, kayaking, zip-lining, paragliding, hiking, exploring, Geocaching, canyoneering, river trekking, sandboarding, caving and rock climbing.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Some obscure forms of adventure travel include disaster and ghetto tourism.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Other rising forms of adventure travel include social and jungle tourism.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Access to inexpensive consumer technology, with respect to Global Positioning Systems, flashpacking, social networking and photography, have increased the worldwide interest in adventure travel.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] The interest in independent adventure travel has also increased as more specialist travel websites emerge offering previously niche locations and sports.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Adventure sports tourism has traditionally been dominated by men.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Although women's participation has grown, the gender gap is still pronounced in terms of quantitative engagement in these forms of sport tourism.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Since ancient times, humans have traveled in search for food and skills of survival, but have also engaged in adventurous travel, in explorations of sea lanes, a destination, or even a new country.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Adventurer travelers began to push to the limits, with the mountaineering of Matterhorn in 1865 and the river rafting on the Colorado River in 1869.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Shortly after, two key institutions were formed, including the National Geographic Society and the Explorers Club, which continue to support adventure travel.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] At the end of World War II, modern adventure began to take off, with the 1950 French Annapurna expedition and the 1953 British Mount Everest expedition.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Today, it remains a niche of travel and a fast-changing sector with new variants of activities for a travel experience.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] There is a trend for developing tourism specifically for disabled people.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Adventure travel for disabled people has become a US$13 billion a year industry in North America.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Some adventure travel destinations offer diverse programs and job opportunities developed specifically for the disabled.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Extreme tourism involves travel to dangerous (*extreme*) locations or participation in dangerous events or activities.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] This form of tourism can overlap with extreme sport.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Travelling to locations far away from human settlements and/or infrastructure.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Could be close to big city (few hours drive) in terms of straight line distance, but reaching the location requires a long period of time and/or a large amount of effort.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Self sufficiency required, as it's difficult to get timely help or rescue in an emergency.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Jungle tourism is a subcategory of adventure travel defined by active multifaceted physical means of travel in the jungle regions of the earth.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] According to the Glossary of Tourism Terms, jungle tours have become a major component of green tourism in tropical destinations and are a relatively recent phenomenon of Western international tourism.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Overland travel or overlanding refers to an overland journey – perhaps originating with Marco Polo's first overland expedition in the 13th century from Venice to the Mongolian court of Kublai Khan.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Today overlanding is a form of extended adventure holiday, embarking on a long journey, often in a group.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Overland companies provide a converted truck or a bus plus a tour leader, and the group travels together overland for a period of weeks or months.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Since the 1960s overlanding has been a popular means of travel between destinations across Africa, Europe, Asia (particularly India), the Americas and Australia.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] The "Hippie trail" of the 60s and 70s saw thousands of young westerners travelling through the Middle East to India and Nepal.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Many of the older traditional routes are still active, along with newer routes like Iceland to South Africa overland and Central Asian post soviet states.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Scuba diving is a sport in which participants explore underwater places while inhaling compressed air from tanks.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Scuba diving is most popular in locations with tropical coral reefs, but it may be found in almost any location with water.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] "Rush as a key motivation in skilled adventure tourism: Resolving the risk recreation paradox".
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] *Centers for Disease Control and Prevention*.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Archived from the original on 13 October 2007.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Apollo, M., Mostowska, J., Legut, A., Maciuk, K., & Timothy, D.
[src:wilderness/adventure-travel] Gender differences in competitive adventure sports tourism.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:wilderness/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:wilderness/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
